        <h3>Introduction to HTML</h3>
    </header>
    <p>HTML is a simple and easy-to-learn language made up of elements. These elements give meaning to text and form the basic building blocks of web development.</p>

    <h4>What is HTML?</h4>
    <p>HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language. It was created in 1991 by Tim Berners-Lee. HTML describes the structure of a web page using elements (tags) that tell the browser how to display content.</p>

    <h4>What is Hypertext?</h4>
    <p>Hypertext is text that links to another text. The entire web is built on links connecting pages together.</p>

    <p><a class="btn btn-link" href="https://www.youtube.com/" target="_blank">YouTube</a> | <a href="https://www.google.com/" target="_blank">Google</a></p>
    <p>For example, clicking "YouTube" takes you to the YouTube homepage. That’s hypertext in action.</p>

    <h4>What is a Markup Language?</h4>
    <p>A markup language uses tags to format content. Examples include HTML, XML, and SGML. Tags define how text and elements are displayed on the screen.</p>

    <p>Example: <b>Dot Net Tutorials</b> → The <code>&lt;b&gt;</code> tag makes text bold.</p>

    <h4>What is a Web Page?</h4>
    <p>A web page is usually written in HTML and displayed in a browser. Pages can be static or dynamic. HTML alone creates static pages.</p>

    <h4>What are Web Browsers?</h4>
    <p>Browsers like Chrome, Edge, Firefox, and Safari read HTML documents and display them. They don’t show the actual tags but interpret them to render content.</p>

    <h4>Versions of HTML</h4>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>HTML 1.0:</strong> Basic version, very limited.</li>
        <li><strong>HTML 2.0:</strong> Introduced in 1995 with improvements.</li>
        <li><strong>HTML 3.2:</strong> Released in 1997 with better tags and CSS support.</li>
        <li><strong>HTML 4.01:</strong> Introduced in 1999, added support for external CSS.</li>
        <li><strong>HTML 5:</strong> The latest version, supports advanced features like multimedia, new form elements, and geolocation.</li>
    </ol>

    <h4>How to Create an HTML Document?</h4>
    <p>Use a text editor like Notepad, VS Code, or Sublime. Save the file with a <code>.html</code> extension so the editor and browser recognize it as HTML.</p>

    <h4>HTML Document Structure</h4>
    <p>An HTML document has this basic structure:</p>

    <ol>
        <li><strong>!DOCTYPE html:</strong> Declares the document type.</li>
        <li><strong>html:</strong> Root element containing everything.</li>
        <li><strong>head:</strong> Metadata like title, links, and scripts.</li>
        <li><strong>title:</strong> Shown on the browser tab.</li>
        <li><strong>body:</strong> Contains all visible content.</li>
        <li><strong>h1–h6:</strong> Headings for content hierarchy.</li>
    </ol>
